<BlogArticle title="Hubs, Alliances, and World Cup Mobility" subtitle="The tournament temporarily reweights airline network flows, making connectivity and centrality more important than match counts alone." category="Aviation Networks" date="June 20, 2026" readingTime="7 min read" tags={['Aviation Networks','Network Centrality','Airline Alliances','Passenger Flows']} image={`${base}project-previews/hub-atlas.svg`} imageAlt="Stylized U.S. airline hub map with connecting routes">
  <p class="lead">The World Cup does not create a new airline network. It temporarily changes the amount, direction, and timing of flow across the network that already exists.</p>
  <p>That distinction matters. A list of extra flights treats every movement as an isolated event. Network analysis asks a different set of questions: Which nodes concentrate the flow? Which connections become temporarily important? Where do many plausible journeys depend on the same hub? How does a change at one node affect paths elsewhere?</p>
  <p>Seen this way, the 2026 tournament is not mainly an aviation-demand story. It is a temporary reconfiguration of airline network flows.</p>

  <h2>Alliance Geography</h2>
  <p>Geographic distance does not fully explain how supporters reach a host city. Airline alliances overlay their own geography on the physical map. They connect home markets, long-haul gateways, U.S. hubs, and final destinations through schedules and commercial partnerships.</p>
  <p>A Germany-related journey illustrates the idea. Lufthansa and United belong to Star Alliance, so a supporter may encounter an itinerary through IAH, ORD, EWR, DEN, or SFO depending on the origin and match destination. The relevant network is not simply Germany to the nearest American airport. It is a set of alliance-compatible paths linking European origins to United's connecting structure.</p>
  <p>SkyTeam and oneworld produce different path sets. SkyTeam can channel some European, Asian, or Latin American flows through nodes such as ATL, JFK, DTW, or MSP. oneworld can connect international gateways at LHR, MAD, or DOH with American Airlines hubs including DFW, MIA, PHL, and CLT.</p>
  <p>These examples are exploratory, not itinerary predictions. Fare, nonstop service, loyalty programs, capacity, and schedule timing still matter. The network insight is that supporters with similar destinations can move through different U.S. nodes because their origin markets sit inside different alliance geographies.</p>
  <div class="dark-visual"><div class="flow-stack"><span>International origin markets<small>Europe · Latin America · Asia</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Alliance networks<small>Star Alliance · SkyTeam · oneworld</small></span><i>↓</i><span class="active">U.S. gateway and connecting hubs<small>Alternative paths through a shared national network</small></span><i>↓</i><span>World Cup destinations<small>Host city or onward connection</small></span></div></div>

  <h2>Connectivity vs. Geography</h2>
  <p>A host city with more matches does not automatically become the most important aviation node. Match count measures local event load. Connectivity measures how many journeys a node can support, including journeys that continue somewhere else.</p>
  <p>Consider an airport that hosts no local match but connects dozens of origins to several host cities. It can carry more tournament-related transfer traffic than a host-city airport with limited nonstop service. ORD and DEN may matter to the tournament because of the paths they organize, not because a stadium sits nearby.</p>
  <p>This is the difference between geographic importance and network importance. Geography asks where the match is. Network analysis asks which nodes make the match reachable.</p>
  <p>Several forms of centrality help clarify that distinction. Degree centrality describes how many direct connections a hub has. Weighted degree can give more importance to frequent or high-capacity links. Betweenness centrality asks how often a node lies on useful paths between other nodes. A hub with high betweenness may become critical even when it is neither the origin nor destination of most supporters.</p>
  <div class="comparison">
    <div><span>Measure</span><strong>What it captures</strong><strong>World Cup interpretation</strong></div>
    <div><span>Match count</span><strong>Local event frequency</strong><strong>Potential destination demand</strong></div>
    <div><span>Degree</span><strong>Number of direct links</strong><strong>Available nonstop reach</strong></div>
    <div><span>Weighted connectivity</span><strong>Strength of linked service</strong><strong>Capacity across useful corridors</strong></div>
    <div><span>Betweenness</span><strong>Position on connecting paths</strong><strong>Dependence on transfer hubs</strong></div>
  </div>

  <h2>The World Cup as a Network Flow Problem</h2>
  <p>In a network model, airports are nodes, scheduled services are edges, and passengers create flow. The World Cup temporarily changes the flow without immediately changing most of the underlying topology. The same routes remain, but some carry more supporters, some become directional, and some become important only after a team advances.</p>
  <p>Normal leisure travel is often represented as a round trip: A to B and back to A. Team-following behavior can create an open chain: home country, first host city, second host city, possible knockout destination, then home. The reverse flow may not match the outbound flow.</p>
  <p>This creates temporary corridors. A Germany supporter might enter through Houston, continue toward another group-stage match, and branch again after qualification. A team elimination can end that corridor; an unexpected qualification can activate another. The bracket therefore acts like a rule that dynamically reassigns passenger demand across edges.</p>
  <p>Airlines cannot redesign their full schedules after every result. The network absorbs much of the change through fuller flights, connecting itineraries, prices, and limited capacity adjustments. The operational question is whether existing paths can carry the reweighted flow while retaining enough flexibility for ordinary travelers and recovery from disruption.</p>
  <div class="dark-visual"><div class="flow-stack"><span>Existing airline network<small>Mostly fixed nodes and scheduled edges</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Tournament schedule and results<small>Demand changes by time and destination</small></span><i>↓</i><span class="active">Temporarily reweighted passenger flows<small>Directional corridors and shared hubs</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Network outcomes<small>Load concentration · rerouting · propagation risk</small></span></div></div>

  <h2>Why Alliance Networks Matter More in 2026 than in 2022</h2>
  <p>Qatar 2022 concentrated eight stadiums in and around one metropolitan region. Airline networks were essential for reaching the host country, but most supporters did not need a new flight between matches. Once they arrived, the tournament operated largely through local ground transportation.</p>
  <p>North America 2026 has a different topology from the traveler's perspective. Sixteen host cities are distributed across three countries and several time zones. Aviation can serve both as the entrance to the tournament and as an internal connection between fixtures.</p>
  <p>That makes alliance networks more consequential. They influence which long-haul gateways connect efficiently to domestic networks, which hubs offer protected connections, and which paths remain practical when a supporter changes cities. In 2022, alliance geography primarily organized arrival into a compact destination. In 2026, it can organize a sequence of movements across the tournament.</p>
  <p>The difference is not that alliances suddenly become more powerful. The geography of the event gives their existing structure more opportunities to shape mobility.</p>

  <h2>Connectivity, Centrality, and World Cup Mobility</h2>
  <p>My <a href="https://yuhexin25-oss.github.io/us-airline-hub-atlas/">U.S. Airline Hub Atlas</a> provides a way to see this structure. It scales airport markers with FAA CY2024 enplanements, separates hubs and focus cities, and uses a static route snapshot to show how carrier networks concentrate around selected nodes.</p>
  <article class="project-block"><img src={`${base}project-previews/hub-atlas.svg`} alt="U.S. Airline Hub Atlas preview showing route arcs and airport nodes" loading="lazy" /><div><h3>Reading the network</h3><p>The atlas makes airport hierarchy visible: node size represents passenger scale, route links show reach, and carrier filters reveal that the national network is composed of overlapping airline-specific structures.</p></div></article>
  <p>The atlas does not calculate a definitive World Cup centrality ranking. It supports the more important analytical step: separating airport size, local match load, and connectivity. ATL may matter because it combines scale with dense connectivity. IAH can be both a Houston destination and a transfer node. ORD and DEN can influence host-city access despite not hosting matches.</p>
  <p>The same structure connects to my delay work. The <a href="https://yuhexin25-oss.github.io/usflightdelay/">U.S. Flight Delay Analysis</a> prototype organizes questions about concentration and transmission, while the <a href="https://yuhexin25-oss.github.io/livedelayanalysis/">Live Delay Analysis Dashboard</a> explores current hub exposure. Together, the projects move from topology, to historical behavior, to operational awareness.</p>
  <p>That progression matters because centrality has two sides. A central hub creates access and alternative destinations. It also concentrates dependency. When a highly connected node slows, more passenger paths can be affected than its local traffic count alone suggests.</p>
  <div class="dark-visual"><div class="flow-stack"><span>Network structure<small>Nodes, edges, alliances, and centrality</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Temporary flow reconfiguration<small>Teams, supporters, and conditional destinations</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Concentrated dependency<small>Shared paths through central hubs</small></span><i>↓</i><span class="active">World Cup network performance<small>Accessibility, resilience, and propagation</small></span></div></div>

  <h2>A temporary network, built on a permanent one</h2>
  <p>The World Cup is better understood as a network phenomenon than as a collection of individual flights. Match locations define destinations, alliances shape feasible paths, hubs concentrate connections, and tournament results reweight flows over time.</p>
  <p>The physical network remains mostly permanent. The flow pattern does not. That temporary mismatch is the central research problem: a network optimized for ordinary demand must absorb directional, uncertain, and rapidly changing movement without losing resilience.</p>

